rComments: I have so much respect for Professor Jenkins. Interesting and thorough lectures. Make sure you listen for the films and books she mentions while lecturing as they're all so interesting and good to watch/read in your spare time. Accessible office hours and straightforward assignment/test grading criteria.

Prof. Jenkins is my new favourite professor ever. You won't want to skip out on the readings - they're actually really great and she curates them so well. She gives really good feedback on all assignments and tests and rewards engagement. She seems tough, but really she just cares a lot and doesn't have a lot of patience for BS.
teacherRatingTags: ['Amazing lectures', 'Get ready to read', 'Gives good feedback']

rComments: Professor Jenkins was a really great prof. She was passionate about the topics and took the time to thoroughly explain each event, person and term she was talking about which was great. Her midterm was extremely easy. She gives outlines for her lectures but you need to go to class to understand fully so make sure you go.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Amazing lectures', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: Professor Jenkins is very knowledgeable in her field. She was pretty accessible too and once I got to know her, she was more warm than she appears. That being said, sometimes she can be aloof to the student condition or exhibit a holier than thou attitude.

Prof. Jenkins might not be a perfect lecturer, and her slides are more of pictures than words, but she's the most approachable professor I've ever met. She's extremely knowledgeable and is definitely helpful outside the classroom. Tests and assignments are reasonable, her TAis also amazing. There are also extra credits for watching films.

Professor Jenkins was very knowledgeable about German history, and her slides contained a wealth of pictures that were supplemented by primary source documents. However, later in the year she did have a tendency to drift off topic on 20th and 21st Century issues, often running out of time on many lecture topics

She often went so far off topic or asked for class opinions on images that she ran out of time to cover material, which she later complained she never had enough time (the lecture was 2 hrs long). Although she provided a clear outline in the form of a document that notes could be added directly into, I was often lost because of her lack of focus.
teacherRatingTags: ['Participation matters', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Test heavy']

rComments: Professor Jenkins was wonderful. Her lectures were clear and she was definitely knowledgeable about German history.  She was also extremely  helpful outside of class and was  available for appointments outside regular office hours. The grading scheme was fairly straightforward as were her testsessays. It was a great course and I would recommend it
She was great and so enthusiastic about the course material.

Professor Jenkins was great for this course. We had a variety of primary sources, books and movies which made the course great. The only problem I had was that we did not get through all of the lecture notes in her slide. The TA more than made up for it and her tutorials were the best I have had at U of T, and I have heard the same from others.
Best professor I ever had.

She's a great prof. He lectures are interesting, the textbook is very helpful and the readings are engaging. The pictures she uses in class are very graphic though and she leaves them up for a long time. Overall one of my favourite professors. She also holds movie screenings for extra credit.
She is very helpful and understanding. She is fair to the students. Although you should work hard for getting a good grade, I really recommend you to take her courses.She is brilliant.

awesome prof! she is not the most compelling lecturer (and its a 2 hr class without breaks) but she is extremely knowledgeable in her field (german history), and very personable! she really seems to care about students and how we're engaging with course material. she's also incredibly approachable. Def a good experience!

She is a great prof. She lived in Berlin for a lot of years and her experiences are illustrated in the classroom. She has a lot of visuals, updated movies. She is very calm and patient with everything. I took 2 of her classes and enjoyed them both. Watch out for the TAs though, they can mess up your grade.
Loved her, Don't need to attend class that often to do well. Just read the textbook before Tutorial and exams and you will get an A.

Her organization of the course left a lot to be desired. Textbook readings were thick with way too much detail. Essay prospectus was due too early (more than one month before deadline). Exam questions dealt with some of the topics she spent the least time in lecture. Overall quite disappointing and not recommendable.
very vague and disorganized. Puts the lecture outline up 5 minutes before class so no one has a chance to download it and goes off topic and reads quotes WAY too much.
Goes off topic too much

Absolutely USELESS. Her lectures are not only mind-numbingly boring but filled with gaps, which is strange since she never makes it through her lecture material. I had to use the text book to essentially teach myself the course for the midterm. I'm curious to see how she'll manage to actually get through all the course material...
Super cool and fun! Also super bright!!!

An excellent professor, really brilliant, though you really have to pay attention: she does not make it easy for you.  If you don't get it (ie. her lectures) then drop history.  Not conceited at all (maybe socially awkward, yes) but very charming and helpful. Best professor I ever had (top three, at any rate).
super-duper conceited.
Knows her stuff inside and out, is brilliant, and super-duper nice. Can't recommend her highly enough!
Lousy lecturer yes, but also a mean-spirited person. Acts like she's hot s--t when she's not. Acts like she's queen, when god knows she's not. A very conceited woman.

Not a good lecturer at all. The concept of a lecture outline seemed foreign to her. She would go off on random tangents that were irrelevant to the course material. She was friendly though and my TA was great, but I hear others were not. I found the exams to be straightforward.

Her lectures were extremely disorganized and hard to follow, and she spoke very quickly. Also, she tested us on things mentionned only fleetingly in lecture and which didn't appear in the textbook or in readings. The format of the final exam made it very hard.

A very boring lecturer, she butchers one of the most exciting and relevent periods in history.However, she is very helpful with students, readings are good, and tests are not hard. She needs to let some passion into her lectures.Unfortunate that because it is under the surface,Matt Price was better.

Jenkins is a great prof. Lectures are fast paced, yes, but also dense and stimulating if you pay attention. She is also admirably student-friendly not only with the care in structuring the course (ie. exam ?s ahead of time), but also in one-on-one consultation during office hours.
Easy tests, gives you questions ahead of time.  my TA was great, Deb Neill, the only reason i did good.
a little boring, but damn cute.  that little hair flip she does? so cute.
very boring lecturer! same with the t.a.'s.  what a great period of history, only she could dull it down so much.

monotonous and monotone lectures. interesting material but presented in the most unattractive manner. the prof concentrates on her own areas of interest instead of all of europe. The TA's are awful and inconsiderate and unhelpful, especially the head TA.

It takes sometime to get used to her lecturing style but its not THAT difficult.She is very attentive to her students and goes the extra mile when you need help, have questions or need advice. I admire that in professors.
